statement:
\textbf{Light Show on the Dance Floor}

\textbf{A laser is mounted 2m above the floor (see sketch) and its beam
is directed along a straight line on the dance floor. For visual
effects, the angle $\theta$ changes periodically and randomly. The angle
$\theta$ is chosen uniformly in the interval
$(-\frac{\pi}{4},\frac{\pi}{4})$, that is, the probability density
function (pdf) is $p(\theta) = \frac{2}{\pi}$ for
$-\frac{\pi}{4} < \theta < \frac{\pi}{4}$ and zero elsewhere.}

\begin{figure}[htbp]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=.5\textwidth]{MATH103_2013Q6.jpg}
\caption{MATH103 2013Q6.jpg }
\end{figure}

Find the cumulative distribution function (cdf), F(x) of the
x-coordinate of the laser point on the floor.

sols:
Solving first for the cdf in terms of $\displaystyle \theta$, using that
\emph{p(t) = 0} for \emph{t \textless{} -$\pi$/4}, we have

\begin{align*}
F(\theta) &= \int_{-\pi/4}^{\theta}\frac{2}{\pi}\,dt = \left.\frac{2}{\pi}t \right|_{-\pi/4}^{\theta} \\
&= \frac{2}{\pi}\left(\theta - \frac{-\pi}4\right)\end{align*}

To find the cdf in terms of \emph{x} we note that, from the diagram,
$\displaystyle \tan(\theta) = \tfrac{x}{2}$. Solving for \emph{$\theta$} gives
$\displaystyle \theta = \arctan(\tfrac{x}{2})$ and thus we have

\begin{align*}\displaystyle F(x) = \frac2{\pi}\left(\arctan\left(\frac{x}{2}\right) + \frac{\pi}{4}\right)\end{align*}

completing the problem.

hints:
Recall the definition of the cumulative distribution function \emph{F}
of a continuous random variable with probability density function
\emph{p}:

\begin{align*}F(\theta) = \int_{-\infty}^\theta p(t)\,dt\end{align*}
